03575nam a22005295i 9780228002888DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280028887 a10.1515/97802280028882doi  a(DE-B1597)654539  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aTK5105.875.I57bM65 2020 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a005.82231 aMolitorisz, Sacha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNet Privacy :bHow We Can Be Free in an Age of Surveillance /cSacha Molitorisz. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: My privacy can set you free -- tI can see the present you, the past you and the future you -- tIt's hard to opt out of a service you've never used -- t‘Technology is neither good nor bad; nor is it neutral’ -- tPrivacy is not all about control -- tMy privacy is for your benefit -- tWhy you cannot consent to selling your soul -- tHow to regulate for dignity -- tWhich way to cosmoikopolis? -- tConclusion: Free together -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn our digital world, we are confused by privacy – what is public, what is private? We are also challenged by it, the conditions of privacy so uncertain we become unsure about our rights to it. We may choose to share personal information, but often do so on the assumption that it won't be re-shared, sold, or passed on to other parties without our knowing. In the eighteenth century, philosopher Jeremy Bentham wrote about a new model for a prison called a Panopticon, where inmates surrounded the jailers, always under watch. Have we built ourselves a digital Panopticon? Are we the guards or the prisoners, captive or free? Can we be both? When Kim Kardashian makes the minutiae of her life available online, which is she? With great rigour, this important book draws on a Kantian philosophy of ethics and legal frameworks to examine where we are and to suggest steps – conceptual and practical – to ensure the future is not dystopian. Privacy is one of the defining issues of our time; this lively book explains why this is so, and the ways in which we might protect it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aComputer security. 0aConsumer protection. 0aData protection. 0aInternetxSafety measures. 0aInternetxSecurity measures. 0aInternetxSocial aspects. 0aPrivacy, Right of. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800288840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002888423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002888/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles